"1. Load the three raw datasets from the working directory files u.data, VideoGames.csv, and UserTaggedArtists-timestamps.dat using LensKit 0.14.4-compatible parsing.\n2. Apply 5-core filtering separately to each dataset before any splitting, retaining only users and items with at least 5 interactions after each pruning pass.\n3. Convert MovieLens100K and Amazon Video Games to implicit feedback by keeping only ratings > 3 as positive interactions; treat Last.FM as implicit feedback from the raw interaction signal.\n4. Standardize the data into LensKit feedback format with user IDs, item IDs, and timestamps/ordering preserved where available for reproducible splitting.\n5. Generate exactly 5 distinct random seeds and use each seed to create one user-based 80/20 holdout split per dataset.\n6. Ensure the split is user-based at the user level so every user contributes interactions to both train and test according to the 80/20 holdout protocol, with no leakage between train and test.\n7. Train three LensKit 0.14.4 algorithms\u2014ALS, ItemKNN, and Pop\u2014using standard/default hyperparameters and the same training data for each seed/dataset combination.\n8. Produce top-N recommendation scores for all test users and evaluate nDCG@1, nDCG@5, nDCG@10, Precision@1, Precision@5, and Precision@10 for every algorithm, dataset, and seed.\n9. Use a consistent recommendation cutoff and evaluation protocol across all algorithms and runs, with metric computation restricted to the held-out test items.\n10. Aggregate results over the 5 seeds for each algorithm-dataset pair and report mean and variability (e.g., standard deviation or confidence intervals) for each metric.\n11. Conduct a short statistical analysis quantifying the effect of split random seed on performance, such as per-metric variance across seeds and a simple significance or effect-size comparison across seed runs.\n12. Save intermediate processed datasets, split definitions, per-run metric outputs, and final summary tables so the experiment is reproducible and results can be audited."